A software license means you are giving permission to use the software, not ownership of it.

For example:

Selling the source code ❌
The buyer owns the code.
They can modify it.
They may even resell it (depending on the agreement).
You generally lose exclusive control.
Selling a license ✅
You keep ownership of the software.
The customer only gets the right to use it under your terms.
They cannot legally copy, resell, or distribute it.
You can sell the same product to many different companies.
Example

Suppose your product costs ₹10 lakh.

Company A pays ₹10 lakh.

They receive:

✅ The compiled application
✅ Installation guide
✅ License key
✅ Updates (if included)

They do not receive:

❌ Source code
❌ Git repository
❌ Right to resell
❌ Right to claim ownership

Then Company B can also buy the same product for ₹10 lakh under a separate license.

What should your license say?

Your agreement should include terms such as:

The software is licensed, not sold.
The source code remains your property.
Redistribution or resale is prohibited.
Reverse engineering is prohibited where allowed by law.
The license is valid only for the purchasing company.
The software may only be installed on the agreed number of computers.
Support and updates are provided according to the purchased plan.

This is the standard model used by many software companies: customers pay for the right to use the software, while the developer keeps ownership and can license it to multiple customers.

How to do that 

You don't need a complicated system to start. The goal is to make it easy for customers to use while protecting your software and business.

Here's a practical approach:

1. Keep your source code private
Never send the project folder.
Never send your Git repository.
Build the application into executable files (.exe) and package everything needed to run it.
2. Generate a license key

For each customer, create a unique license key, for example:

ALIFF-ABC123-2026-9XK8

The software checks this key when it starts.

3. Lock the license

Bind the license to:

One company, or
One PC (using a machine ID), or
A fixed number of computers.

If someone copies the software to another machine, the license won't activate there.

4. Add activation

On first launch:

Customer enters the license key.
The software validates it (online or offline, depending on your design).
If valid, it stores the activation locally.
5. Use a license agreement

Provide a simple agreement stating:

The software is licensed, not sold.
You retain ownership.
No redistribution or resale.
No source code is provided.
Support and updates are covered separately.
6. Charge separately for support

For example:

One-time license fee.
Optional annual maintenance/support fee.
Custom features billed separately.
Can they still reverse-engineer it?

No protection is perfect. A determined expert may be able to inspect compiled software. Your goal is to make it difficult enough that it's not worth the effort by:

Compiling and bundling the app.
Obfuscating the code where appropriate.
Using license checks.
Relying on legal agreements in addition to technical protection.

For a product like yours that companies may pay lakhs of rupees for, it's also worth considering hiring a software licensing specialist or using a commercial licensing system before your first major sale.

If you're building this with Node.js + Next.js + Fastify + Playwright, I can also suggest an architecture that makes it much harder for customers to access your application logic while still letting them run it locally.

Ok how to convert the web and backend and db as like that

Since your product is built with Next.js + Fastify + PostgreSQL + Redis + Playwright, here's how I'd package it as a commercial Windows application.

Option 1 (Recommended)

Keep the architecture the same but hide the source.

Customer PC
│
├── CLG Search.exe        ← Starts everything
├── API.exe               ← Compiled Fastify backend
├── Dashboard.exe         ← Compiled Next.js frontend
├── PostgreSQL            ← Local database
├── Redis                 ← Local Redis
├── Chromium              ← Playwright browser
└── storage/

The customer only sees executables and data folders—not your project source.

Backend

Compile and bundle the Fastify backend into a single executable using tools such as:

pkg
nexe
@vercel/ncc (bundle first, then package)

The customer runs API.exe, not server.ts or server.js.

Frontend

Instead of shipping the Next.js source:

Build the app.
Bundle it.
Run it behind an executable or package it as a desktop application (for example, using Electron or Tauri if you want a desktop UI).

The customer should never receive your app/, pages/, or source files.

Database

Don't expose SQL scripts unless needed.

Provide:

PostgreSQL installer or embedded PostgreSQL
Automatic database creation
Automatic migrations on first run

The customer only uses the application—they don't manage the database manually.

Redis

Bundle Redis so your launcher starts it automatically.

The customer doesn't need to know Redis is running.

One-click launcher

Create one launcher:

CLG Search.exe

When clicked, it:

Starts PostgreSQL
Starts Redis
Starts the API
Starts the dashboard
Opens the browser or desktop window

From the customer's perspective, it's just one application.

Installer

Create a Windows installer (e.g., with Inno Setup or NSIS) that installs:

C:\Program Files\CLG Search\

containing:

CLG Search.exe
API.exe
Dashboard.exe
chromium\
postgres\
redis\
storage\
license.dat
License checking

On startup:

Read license.dat
        ↓
Validate license
        ↓
If valid → Start application
If invalid → Exit

This lets you issue different licenses to different companies.

Updates

Distribute updates as new installers.

The customer downloads and installs the new version without ever receiving the source code.

Is it completely impossible to extract your code?

No. Any software running on a customer's computer can potentially be reverse-engineered by a skilled attacker. The goal is to make it difficult and impractical, not impossible.

My recommendation

For a product you plan to sell to multiple companies for significant amounts, I would package it as:

✅ One Windows installer
✅ One launcher (CLG Search.exe)
✅ Compiled backend
✅ Compiled frontend
✅ Embedded or automatically configured PostgreSQL and Redis
✅ License key activation
✅ No source code or Git repository provided

This is a common approach for commercial Windows software and lets customers use the product locally while you retain ownership of the code.
The document is well-structured and accurate overall. Here's my honest assessment:
What's good:
The core concepts are correct — licensing vs. selling, keeping source code private, license key generation, binding to machine IDs, and the packaging approach for Next.js + Fastify + PostgreSQL + Redis are all sound advice.
A few things worth improving:
Minor issues:

"where allowed by law" after "reverse engineering is prohibited" is vague — some jurisdictions actually protect reverse engineering rights, so this clause needs a lawyer's review before use in a real contract
The license key example ALIFF-ABC123-2026-9XK8 is fine as an illustration, but real license keys should also include a checksum component to catch typos

Gaps worth adding:

No mention of what happens when a license expires — should the software stop working, or just block updates?
No mention of handling license transfers (what if Company A gets acquired?)
The "Can they reverse-engineer it?" section is honest, but could mention that code signing (signing your .exe with a certificate) is also important — it builds customer trust and prevents tampering warnings from Windows

The Electron/Tauri suggestion for the Next.js frontend is good, but worth noting that Tauri is significantly lighter and harder to reverse-engineer than Electron.
Overall verdict: This is solid guidance for someone starting out. It's not a legal document — it reads correctly as a technical + business guide. Before your first major sale, have a lawyer draft the actual license agreement.